President Trump welcomed three survivors of the USS Arizona to the White House, recognizing their heroic service during the attack on Pearl Harbor in 1941. The survivors, Ken Potts, Lauren Bruner, and Donald Stratton, shared their stories of courage and sacrifice. Ken Potts drove his small boat into the water to rescue passengers from the sinking Arizona. Lauren Bruner and Donald Stratton were rescued by Joe George, who threw a rope onto the ship and helped them escape through the flames. Despite suffering severe burns, both Bruner and Stratton continued to serve in the Navy. President Trump praised their dedication and thanked them for their service. He also honored Joe George, who rescued six men that day. The president emphasized the importance of remembering and honoring the bravery of these veterans and expressed his commitment to strengthening the military.